{"title_page": "The Flight (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1970 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2020}}\n{{For|the unrelated American TV film|The Flight (1988 film)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Flight\n| image          = The_Flight_(film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Aleksandr Alov]]<br>[[Vladimir Naumov]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Mikhail A. Bulgakov]] (play)<br>Aleksandr Alov<br>Vladimir Naumov\n| starring       = [[Lyudmila Savelyeva]]<br>[[Aleksey Batalov]]<br>[[Mikhail Ulyanov]]<br>Tatyana Tkach\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Levan Paatashvili\n| editing        = Tamara Zubova\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|1970}}\n| runtime        = 196 minutes\n| country        = Soviet Union\n| language       = Russian\n}}\n\n'''''The Flight''''' ({{lang-ru|'''\u0411\u0435\u0433'''}}, [[Romanization of Russian|transliteration]] ''Beg'') is a 1970 Soviet [[historical film|historical]] [[drama film]], mainly based on writer [[Mikhail Bulgakov]]'s play ''[[Flight (play)|Flight]]'', but also on his novel ''[[The White Guard]]'' and his libretto ''Black Sea''.<ref>[[:ru:\u0411\u0435\u0433 (\u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c, 1970)|Russian Wikipedia: \u0411\u0435\u0433 (\u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c, 1970)]] Retrieved 26 September 2011</ref> It is written and directed by [[Aleksandr Alov]] and [[Vladimir Naumov]] and is the story about a group of [[White movement|White]] [[refugee]]s from the [[Russian Civil War]], eking out an existence in [[Istanbul]] and [[Paris]] in the 1920s.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0065457/plotsummary IMDb: Plot summary for \"Beg\"] Retrieved 26 September 2011</ref> It was entered into the [[1971 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/2435/year/1971.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Beg |accessdate=12 April 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>  \n\n==Cast==\n* [[Lyudmila Savelyeva]] as Serafima Vladimirovna Korzukhina\n* [[Aleksey Batalov]] as Sergei Pavlovich Golubkov\n* [[Mikhail Ulyanov]] as General Charnota\n* [[Tatyana Tkach]] as Lyuska\n* [[Vladislav Dvorzhetsky]] as General Khludov\n* [[Yevgeniy Yevstigneyev]] as Korzukhin\n* [[Vladimir Zamansky]] as Baev\n* [[Nikolay Olyalin]] as Krapilin\n* [[Bruno Freindlich]] as [[Pyotr Nikolayevich Wrangel|General Vrangel]]\n* [[Vladimir Basov]] as Artur Arturovich, the Cockroach Tsar\n* [[Tamara Loginova]] as Lichiko\n* [[Oleg Yefremov]] as Colonel\n* [[Vladimir Osenev]] as Tikhiy\n* [[Gotlib Roninson]] as Voluptuous Greek\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|id=0065457|title=The Flight}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flight, The}}\n[[Category:1970 films]]\n[[Category:1970s war drama films]]\n[[Category:Soviet films]]\n[[Category:Soviet war drama films]]\n[[Category:Russian war drama films]]\n[[Category:Russian films]]\n[[Category:Russian-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Mikhail Bulgakov]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1920]]\n[[Category:Films set in Crimea]]\n[[Category:Russian Civil War films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Aleksandr Alov]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vladimir Naumovich Naumov]]\n[[Category:Soviet films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films based on Russian novels]]\n\n{{USSR-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1970 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{For|the unrelated American TV film|The Flight (1988 film)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Flight\n| image          = The_Flight_(film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Aleksandr Alov]]<br>[[Vladimir Naumov]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Mikhail A. Bulgakov]] (play)<br>Aleksandr Alov<br>Vladimir Naumov\n| starring       = [[Lyudmila Savelyeva]]<br>[[Aleksey Batalov]]<br>[[Mikhail Ulyanov]]<br>Tatyana Tkach\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Levan Paatashvili\n| editing        = Tamara Zubova\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|1970}}\n| runtime        = 196 minutes\n| country        = Soviet Union\n| language       = Russian\n}}\n\n'''''The Flight''''' ({{lang-ru|'''\u0411\u0435\u0433'''}}, [[Romanization of Russian|transliteration]] ''Beg'') is a 1970 Soviet [[historical film|historical]] [[drama film]], mainly based on writer [[Mikhail Bulgakov]]'s play ''[[Flight (play)|Flight]]'', but also on his novel ''[[The White Guard]]'' and his libretto ''Black Sea''.<ref>[[:ru:\u0411\u0435\u0433 (\u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c, 1970)|Russian Wikipedia: \u0411\u0435\u0433 (\u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c, 1970)]] Retrieved 26 September 2011</ref> It is written and directed by [[Aleksandr Alov]] and [[Vladimir Naumov]] and is the story about a group of [[White movement|White]] [[refugee]]s from the [[Russian Civil War]], eking out an existence in [[Istanbul]] and [[Paris]] in the 1920s.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0065457/plotsummary IMDb: Plot summary for \"Beg\"] Retrieved 26 September 2011</ref> It was entered into the [[1971 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/2435/year/1971.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Beg |accessdate=12 April 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>  \n\n==Cast==\n* [[Lyudmila Savelyeva]] as Serafima Vladimirovna Korzukhina\n* [[Aleksey Batalov]] as Sergei Pavlovich Golubkov\n* [[Mikhail Ulyanov]] as General Charnota\n* [[Tatyana Tkach]] as Lyuska\n* [[Vladislav Dvorzhetsky]] as General Khludov\n* [[Yevgeniy Yevstigneyev]] as Korzukhin\n* [[Vladimir Zamansky]] as Baev\n* [[Nikolay Olyalin]] as Krapilin\n* [[Bruno Freindlich]] as [[Pyotr Nikolayevich Wrangel|General Vrangel]]\n* [[Vladimir Basov]] as Artur Arturovich, the Cockroach Tsar\n* [[Tamara Loginova]] as Lichiko\n* [[Oleg Yefremov]] as Colonel\n* [[Vladimir Osenev]] as Tikhiy\n* [[Gotlib Roninson]] as Voluptuous Greek\n\n==References==\n{{refl